{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585614"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:14:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:14:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14991"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14991"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.35,0.09,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7679"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115445"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7679"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14991"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97448"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4908"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18766"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18768"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115445"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESuperantigens are bacterial or viral proteins that can cause massive immune system activation and potentially life-threatening conditions like toxic shock syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of T cell activation by superantigens?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Binds to MHC Class I and T cell receptor alpha chain","Binds to MHC Class II and T cell receptor beta chain","Requires processing within antigen presenting cells","Activates only antigen-specific T cells","Binds exclusively to costimulatory molecules"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESuperantigens are unique proteins that cause massive immune activation by simultaneously binding Major Histocompatibility Complex (MHC) Class II molecules on antigen-presenting cells and the variable beta (V\u03b2) region of T cell receptors. This crosslinking leads to widespread T cell activation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinds to MHC Class I and T cell receptor alpha chain\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as superantigens specifically bind to MHC Class II, not Class I, and interact with the beta chain of the T cell receptor. \u003Cstrong\u003ERequires processing within antigen presenting cells\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect since unlike conventional antigens, superantigens bind directly without requiring processing. \u003Cstrong\u003EActivates only antigen-specific T cells\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because superantigens activate T cells regardless of their antigen specificity. \u003Cstrong\u003EBinds exclusively to costimulatory molecules\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the primary binding is to MHC II and TCR, not costimulatory molecules. This non-specific activation can stimulate up to 20% of all T cells, leading to massive cytokine release that can cause toxic shock syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Superantigens bind to MHC Class II and TCR V\u03b2 region to cause widespread, non-specific T cell activation without requiring antigen processing","Superantigens can activate up to 20% of all T cells, leading to massive cytokine release","Superantigens are important virulence factors in bacterial infections like toxic shock syndrome"],"references":["Esensten JH, Helou YA, Chopra G, Weiss A, Bluestone JA. CD28 Costimulation: From Mechanism to Therapy. Immunity. 2016 May 17;44(5):973-88. doi: 10.1016/j.immuni.2016.04.020. PMID: 27192564; PMCID: PMC4932896","Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Alberts B, Johnson A, Lewis J, et al. Molecular Biology of the Cell. 4th edition. New York: Garland Science; 2002. Helper T Cells and Lymphocyte Activation. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK26827/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97448"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14991"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97448"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T18:35:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T18:35:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7679"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115445"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)